#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/lena/skills/marketing-and-growth/cold-email/references/subject-lines.md savings=8%
M|Subj|The |**short, boring, internal-looking subject lines win decisively.**
M|Leng|it|2-word subject lines get **60% more opens** than 5-word (Lavender).
M|Leng|it|Going from 2 to 4 words reduces replies by **17.5%**.
M|Leng|it|2–4 words yield **46% open rates** vs 34% for 10 words (Belkins, 5.5M emails).
M|Leng|it|Mobile truncates at 30–35 characters — brevity is practical necessity.
M|Inte|tx|Subject lines that look like they came from a colleague, not a vendor, double open rates (Gong). Buyers mentally categorize before opening — if it looks like sales, it's filtered.
M|Inte|**Hi|** "reply rates" · "trial delays" · "hiring ops" · "employee turnover" · "Q2 fc" · "new patients" · "personalization issue" · "second page"
M|Capi|tx|All-lowercase has highest open rates (Gong, 85M+ emails). Lowercase looks more personal/internal. For cold outreach specifically, lowercase beats title case.
M|Pers|Pers|
M|Pers|it|**First name in subject line → 12% fewer replies.** Signals automation.
M|Pers|- **|** pain points, cr, trigger events, industry challenges.
M|Pers|it|Use {{painPoint}}, {{cr}}, {{commonGround}} — not {{firstName}}.
M|Ques|Data|Belkins says questions perform well (46% open rate). Lavender says questions lower opens by **56%**. Resolution: **specific pain questions work** ("Need help w/ {{challenge}}?"), **generic questions fail** ("Quick question?" / "Have 15 minutes?"). Default to statements.
M|What|tx|\| Anti-pattern                                   \| Impact                      \|
M|What|tx|\| ---------------------------------------------- \| --------------------------- \|
M|What|tx|\| Salesy language ("increase," "boost," "ROI")   \| -17.9% opens                \|
M|What|tx|\| Urgency words ("ASAP," "ur")               \| Below 36% opens             \|
M|What|tx|\| Excessive punctuation ("!!!" or "??")          \| -36% opens                  \|
M|What|tx|\| Numbers and percentages                        \| -46% opens                  \|
M|What|tx|\| Emojis                                         \| Hurt B2B professionalism    \|
M|What|tx|\| Pitching pd in subject                    \| -57% replies                \|
M|What|tx|\| Empty/no subject line                          \| +30% opens but -12% replies \|
M|What|tx|\| Spam triggers ("free," "guarantee," "act now") \| Deliverability risk         \|
M|C-Su|tx|Executives receive 300–400 emails daily, decide in seconds. They respond **23% more often** than non-C-suite when emails pass their filter (6.4% reply rate).
M|C-Su|What|ultra-concise, human, understated. "{{companyInitiative}}" · "thank you" · "an up" · "a question" · reference to a specific project or trigger event.
M|C-Su|tx|Anything "salesy" is immediately rejected.